In trapezoid $ABCD$ with bases $\overline{AB}$ and   $\overline{CD}$, we have $AB = 52$, $BC = 12$, $CD = 39$, and $DA = 5$. What is the area of $ABCD$?

[asy]
pair A,B,C,D;
A=(0,0);
B=(4,0);
C=(3.3,1);
D=(0.3,1);
label("$A$",A,S);
label("$B$",B,S);
label("$C$",C,N);
label("$D$",D,N);
label("52",(2,0),S);
label("39",(1.8,1),N);
label("5",(0.15,0.5),W);
label("12",(3.65,0.5),E);
draw(A--B--C--D--cycle);
[/asy]

solution:
First drop perpendiculars from $D$ and $C$ to $\overline{AB}$. Let $E$ and $F$ be the feet of the perpendiculars to $\overline{AB}$ from $D$ and $C$, respectively,  and let $$
h = DE = CF, \quad x = AE, \quad\text{and}\quad y = FB.
$$[asy]
pair A,B,C,D;
A=(0,0);
B=(4,0);
C=(3.3,1);
D=(0.3,1);
draw(D--(0.3,0));
draw(C--(3.3,0));
label("$E$",(0.3,0),SE);
label("$F$",(3.3,0),S);
label("$x$",(0.15,0),S);
label("$y$",(3.65,0),S);
label("$h$",(0.3,0.5),E);
label("$h$",(3.3,0.5),W);
label("$A$",A,SW);
label("$B$",B,S);
label("$C$",C,N);
label("$D$",D,N);
label("39",(2,0),S);
label("39",(1.8,1),N);
label("5",(0.15,0.5),W);
label("12",(3.65,0.5),E);
draw(A--B--C--D--cycle);
[/asy] Then $$
25 = h^2 + x^2, \quad 144 = h^2 + y^2, \quad\text{and}\quad 13 = x+y.
$$So $$
144 = h^2 + y^2 = h^2 + (13-x)^2 = h^2 + x^2 + 169 - 26x = 25 + 169- 26x,
$$which gives    $x = 50/26 = 25/13$, and $$
h= \sqrt{5^2 - \left(\frac{25}{13}\right)^2} = 5\sqrt{1 - \frac{25}{169}}
= 5\sqrt{\frac{144}{169}} = \frac{60}{13}.
$$Hence $$
\text{Area }(ABCD) = \frac{1}{2}(39 + 52)\cdot\frac{60}{13} = \boxed{210}.
$$$$
\text{OR}
$$Extend  $\overline{AD}$  and  $\overline{BC}$  to intersect at $P$. Since $\triangle PDC$ and $\triangle PAB$ are similar, we have $$
\frac{PD}{PD + 5} = \frac{39}{52} =
\frac{PC}{PC+12}.
$$So $PD = 15$ and $PC = 36$. Note that $15$, $36$, and $39$ are three times $5$, $12$, and $13$, respectively, so $\angle APB$ is a right angle. The area of the trapezoid is the difference of the areas of $\triangle PAB$ and $\triangle PDC$, so $$
\text{Area}(ABCD) =\frac{1}{2}(20)(48) - \frac{1}{2}(15)(36) = \boxed{210}.
$$[asy]
pair A,B,C,D;
A=(0,0);
B=(4,0);
C=(3.3,1);
D=(0.3,1);
label("$A$",A,S);
label("$B$",B,S);
label("$C$",C,E);
label("$D$",D,W);
draw((1.2,4)--C--D--cycle);
label("$P$",(1.2,4),N);
draw(A--B--C--D--cycle);
[/asy] $$
\text{OR}
$$Draw the line through $D$ parallel to  $\overline{BC}$, intersecting  $\overline{AB}$ at $E$. Then $BCDE$ is a parallelogram, so $DE = 12$, $EB = 39$, and $AE = 52 - 39 = 13.$ Thus $DE^2 + AD^2 = AE^2$, and  $\triangle ADE$ is a right triangle. Let $h$ be the altitude from $D$ to  $\overline{AE}$, and note that $$
\text{Area}(ADE) = \frac{1}{2}(5)(12) = \frac{1}{2}(13)(h),
$$so $h = 60/13$. Thus $$
\text{Area}(ABCD) =\frac{60}{13}\cdot\frac{1}{2}(39 + 52) = \boxed{210}.
$$[asy]
pair A,B,C,D;
A=(0,0);
B=(4,0);
C=(3.3,1);
D=(0.3,1);
label("$A$",A,S);
label("$B$",B,S);
label("$C$",C,N);
label("$D$",D,N);
draw(D--(1,0));
label("$E$",(1,0),S);
draw(A--B--C--D--cycle);
[/asy]

We begin by drawing a diagram and labeling the vertices $A$, $B$, and $C$ as shown:

[asy]
pair A, B, C;
A=(0,0); B=(17,0); C=(5,12);
draw(A--B--C--cycle);
label("$A$",A,W); label("$B$",B,E); label("$C$",C,N);
label("$13$",(A+C)/2,NW); label("$12\sqrt{2}$",(B+C)/2,NE); label("$17$",(A+B)/2,S);
[/asy]

We drop a perpendicular from $C$ to $\overline{AB}$ and label the intersection point $X$. $X$ divides $AB$ into two segments $AX$ and $XB$ that sum to 17, so let $AX=x$ and $XB=17-x$.  Let the height of the triangle, $CX$, have length $h$.

[asy]
pair A, B, C, X;
A=(0,0); B=(17,0); C=(5,12); X=(5,0);
draw(A--B--C--cycle); draw(C--X);
label("$A$",A,W); label("$B$",B,E); label("$C$",C,N); label("$X$",X,S);
label("$13$",(A+C)/2,NW); label("$12\sqrt{2}$",(B+C)/2,NE); label("$x$",(A+X)/2,S); label("$17-x$",(B+X)/2,S);
label("$h$",(C+X)/2,E);
draw(rightanglemark(C,X,B,20));
[/asy]

Now we have two right triangles, so we can use the Pythagorean theorem on both triangles to write two equations in terms of $x$ and $h$.  From $\triangle AXC$, we have \[x^2+h^2=13^2,\] and from $\triangle CXB$, we have \[(17-x)^2+h^2=(12\sqrt{2})^2.\] Expanding the second equation gives $289-34x+x^2+h^2=144\cdot 2 = 288$; substituting the first equation into the second gives \[289-34x+13^2=288.\] Simplifying and solving for $x$ yields $1+169=34x$, so $x=170/34=5$.  Plugging this value into the first equation gives \[h^2=13^2-x^2=169-25=144,\] so $h=\sqrt{144}=12$.  Finally, we can compute the area of $\triangle ABC$ to be \[\frac{1}{2}(AB)(h)=\frac{1}{2}(17)(12)=\boxed{102}.\]

